messages.com.vmware.loginsight.web.settings.stats:
The actual ingestion rate (syslog + API) of each node after message rebalancing.
Log Insight nodes will rebalance messages to attempt uniform ingestion per node for balanced retention and performance.

Note that the ingestion rate of each node must be below the ingestion rate configuration maximum for a node.

For the actual rate of events being sent directly to each node prior to message rebalancing, see the Syslog Events Incoming Rate (Per Second) and API Events Incoming Rate (Per Second) tables below.

The incoming rate of Syslog events being sent directly to each node by devices.
The incoming rate is calculated prior to message rebalancing and does not reflect the actual ingestion rate per node.

It is acceptable, expected and supported for the incoming rate on a node -- such as the ILB -- to be greater than the ingestion rate configuration maximum for a node as message rebalancing will fairly distribute the load.

For the actual ingestion rate, see the Events Ingestion Rate (Per Second) table above.

The incoming rate of API events being sent directly to each node by devices.
The incoming rate is calculated prior to message rebalancing and does not reflect the actual ingestion rate per node.

It is acceptable, expected and supported for the incoming rate on a node -- such as the ILB -- to be greater than the ingestion rate configuration maximum for a node as message rebalancing will fairly distribute the load.

For the actual ingestion rate, see the Events Ingestion Rate (Per Second) table above.

How many queries each node is running.
It is expected for some nodes to have more queries than others, however during times of congestion a small subset of nodes may have a large list of active queries.
For more information on running queries, see the Active Queries tab.

The ingestion queue is used to ensure Log Insight can keep up with the ingestion rate especially during spikes in ingestion.
Even during normal operations the queue may be used.

• Memory Utilized/Capacity - memory queue, once full disk queue is used

• Disk Size - disk utilization of current block, once full another disk block will be created

• Disk Blocks - number of disk blocks, once full events either need to be consumed by other nodes in the cluster else they will be dropped

Disk Blocks is the most important metric. It is normal to have disk blocks and in the case of a cluster having a small subset of nodes with 70 disk blocks is OK.
Indications of a problem are when either majority/all of the nodes are at 70 or when queries are too slow at the same time as having 50+ disk blocks on the majority/all nodes.

This table contains information about caching.
For the best performance, the number of hits should be greater than the number of misses, however depending on the events and the types of queries being issued it is not uncommon for misses to be greater than hits.

• Evictions refer to cache that has been removed to make room for new cache in an attempt to optimize performance.

• Removals refer to cache that has been removed because it has not been referenced in awhile.

The origin refers to where the query originated from:

Interactive Analytics
• Chart - visualization above the search bar
• Events - tab below the search bar
• Event Types - tab below the search bar
• Event Trends - tab below the search bar
• Alerts - from the alert icon to the right of the search bar
• Facet - chart when expanding a field

Internal
• Precompute - cache queries
• Schema - machine learning queries
• Tools - internal-only
• Other - internal-only

The number of subqueries (bucket query tasks), since restart, that have been issued against each node, broken down by the query source.
The unit of cost is a bucket.

This table contains information about repository caching.
For the best performance, the number of hits should be greater than the number of misses, however depending on the events and the types of queries being issued it is not uncommon for misses to be greater than hits.

Additional information about syslog events including:

• Active TCP Sessions - this number should be less than the configuration maximum per node

• Total TCP Sessions - the total number of syslog TCP sessions that have been created against that server since its most recent restart

• Memory Utilized/Capacity - queue information

• Messages Enqueued - number of events in the ingestion pipeline that have not been processed yet

• Syslog Exceptions - errors encountered extracting syslog events out of the TCP connections or UDP packets. Typically this happens because the client TCP connection is terminated ungracefully.

• Truncated Events - events that exceed the syslog RFC maximum that have been reduced in size to meet the RFC
The sum of Syslog Events and API Events.

The rate of messages received at each node via the syslog protocol.
The total events ingestion rate might be lower than incoming rate if the incoming rate is higher than sustained ingestion capacity of the cluster.

The rate of messages received at each node via API.
The total events ingestion rate might be lower than incoming rate if the incoming rate is higher than sustained ingestion capacity of the cluster.

Buckets that need to be archived, but have not been.

This may indicate an archive, configuration or network issue.
Log Insight will send a system notification when archiving issues occurs and will catch up once the archiving issue is resolved.

This data set restricts other data sets

The 'restrict' checkbox determines how a data set should behave when combined with other data sets. For example, if you have two data sets:

Data set 1:
hostname contains "host"
appname contains "app"

Data set 2:
severity contains "error"

If both of these data sets are added to a role, the resulting combined data set would be:
(hostname contains "host" AND appname contains "app") OR (severity contains "error")

However, if the 'restrict' checkbox is checked for data set 2, the combined data set would be:
(hostname contains "host" AND appname contains "app") AND (severity contains "error")
Data Sets are used to provide users with access to specific content. They are comprised of a set of filters that can then be associated with a Role.
Roles are associated with permissions that allow users to perform different actions within Log Insight, and with Data Sets that give users access to specific content.

Tags allow you to add fields with pre-defined values to events for easier querying.
One or more filters can be defined to restrict which events are forwarded to the configured destination. If no filter is specified then all events will be forwarded.

The port to which events should be sent on the remote destination. The default value is set based on the protocol specified and should not be changed unless the remote destination listens on a different port.

The amount of local disk space to reserve for buffering events that are configured to be forwarded. Buffering is used when the remote destination is unavailable or unable to process the events currently being sent to it. If the local buffer becomes full and the remote destination is still unavailable then the oldest local events will be dropped and not forwarded to the remote destination even when the remote destination is back online.

The number of simultaneous outgoing connections to use. Normally higher worker count is needed for higher network latency to the forwarded destination and for higher events per second being forwarded.

Event forwarding can be used to send filtered and/or tagged events to one or more remote destinations (Log Insight and/or syslog). This feature can be used to support existing logging tools (e.g. SIEM) as well as consolidate logging over different networks (e.g. DMZ and/or WAN).

Note: Event forwarder(s) can be standalone or clustered, but they are completely separate instance(s) from the remote destination. Instances configured for event forwarding also store events locally and can be used to query data.

Additionally, the corresponding trusted root certificate must be imported into the certificate store of the forwarder instance.

Log Insight features an Integrated Load Balancer (ILB) which supports one or more Virtual IP Address (VIPs). Each VIP balances incoming ingestion and query traffic fairly among available Log Insight nodes. Each VIP also ensures that incoming ingestion and query traffic is accepted even if some Log Insight nodes become unavailable. It is recommended that all Log Insight clients, using the web user interface and/or ingestion (via Syslog or the API), connect to Log Insight via a VIP defined below and not directly to a node.

It is strongly recommended that the Integrated Load Balancer (ILB) be enabled. The ILB balances incoming ingestion traffic fairly among available Log Insight nodes. The ILB also ensures that incoming ingestion traffic is accepted even if some Log Insight nodes become unavailable. Log Insight clients, using both the web user interface and ingestion (via Syslog or the API), should connect to Log Insight via the specified ILB IP address.

The ILB requires that all Log Insight nodes be on the same Layer 2 network, such as behind the same switch or otherwise able to receive ARP requests from and send ARP responses to each other. The ILB IP address should be chosen so that any Log Insight node can own it and receive traffic for it. Typically, this means that the ILB IP address will be in the same subnet as the physical address of the Log Insight nodes. After you configure the ILB IP address, try to ping it from a different network to ensure that it is routable.

To simplify future changes and upgrades, it is recommended to have clients point to a FQDN that resolves to the ILB IP address, instead of pointing directly to the ILB IP address. vSphere integration and alert messages will use FQDN if provided otherwise it will use ILB IP address. Log Insight should be able to resolve FQDN to given IP address.

OSI (Operating System Instance) licensing is based the number of systems sending log data to Log Insight. An OSI is identified by a hostname, including but not limited to, virtualized physical servers, storage arrays and network devices.

CPU licensing is based on the number of physical processors on an ESXi host and includes licensing for the ESXi plus all VMs running on the host.

A TAP license is an Evaluation License for VMware Technology Alliance Partners. This license may only be used for evaluation purposes in a non-production environment.

A vCenter license provides 25 OSI licenses.

The Active Average OSI count is the average daily number of hosts sending events to Log Insight. To remain in compliance with an OSI license, the average should not exceed the total OSI license quantity.

Requirements for the custom certificate file:
  1. The certificate file contains both a valid private key and a valid certificate chain.
  2. The private key is generated by the RSA or the DSA algorithm.
  3. The private key is not encrypted by a pass phrase.
  4. If the certificate is signed by a chain of other certificates, all other certificates must be included in the certificate file that you plan to import.
  5. All the certificates and the private key that are included in the certificate file must be PEM-encoded. DER-encoded certificates and private keys are not supported.
  6. All the certificates and the private key that are included in the certificate file must be in the PEM format. Certificates in the PFX, PKCS12, PKCS7, or other formats are not supported.
